content.description: Start left on a crescent shaped side pull and right on an underclimg pinch feature. Use heel hooks to work up to holds on the lip. From here top out straight up or move slightly left and top out there.
content.location: Head all the way up to the head of Comanche Canyon and look left for the boulder that sits just in front of the wall. The problem climbs the far arete of that boulder.

content.description: Start at the bottom of the roof on horizontals. Move to the rail and then climb to the end of the roof. From here, climb left on huecos and mantle at the point.
The crux is pulling the roof   I like roofs   Good warm up
content.location: hueco,east mountain, water dog wall   climb stright up 4ft. right of the roof crack.   finish to the left   jump down onto pads

content.description: Sit start. Go up and left to the glory jug. Nice little rig on bullet rock.

Stellar looking line that improbably makes a reasonable boulder problem. Multiple place you could start, the lowest of which would involve a series of long pulls on positive edges while exposing yourself to a poor landing with evidence that some of those edges have crumbled.  

  However, if you start from the middle landing area from a high right edge and a seam the rock is very good and there are only really 2 moves that feel exposed. From the crimp work your way up the seam until you can reach out right to an edge in a horizontal, then punch up to a buggy rail. Move up past another rail and jugs at the top.
content.protection: Pads and multiple spotters to move pads around.
content.location: on the wall at the head of Comanche Canyon. Head up the slab/ramp on the right side of the wall to a landing about 50 feet up.

content.description:
Sheltered and cool (in temperature) 

  Climbing on horizontals out a steep wall/roof over a bad landing. Some other problems around as well. Not the best area in the park but possibly the coolest in warm weather. There are a good number of problems and a few of them may even be worth doing if just once.
